# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1920-cleveland-indians-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The **1901 Cleveland Blues season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] It was the franchise's first in the majors, being one of the original franchises of the American League.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Called the "Blues" or "Bluebirds", the team finished seventh out of eight teams.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Spiders were dissolved after winning only 20 games and losing 134 in the 1899 season along with the Louisville Colonels, Baltimore Orioles, and the Washington Senators, leaving the National League with eight teams to begin the 1900 season.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As a result, 1900 marked the first year since 1886 during which the city of Cleveland did not have a team affiliated with Major League Baseball.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] During this time, Cleveland had a minor league baseball team, known as the Bluebirds or Blues due to their all-blue uniforms, which finished their season with a 63–73 record and finished sixth.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The American League became a major league before the 1901 season.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the American League made the jump to major league status, many players jumped ship, including Cy Young and Nap Lajoie, which led the National League to call them an "outlaw league" in November 1900.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the 1901 season came underway in April, and as the war between the two leagues erupted, the Cleveland franchise, now known as the Blues, began its first official season as a Major League Baseball team.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues played their first game of the season against the Chicago White Stockings on April 24, 1901.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] This was the first games in the history of the American League; three other games scheduled that day were rained out.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The starting lineup consisted of: Ollie Pickering (RF), Jack McCarthy (LF), Frank Genins (CF), Candy LaChance (1B), Bill Bradley (3B), Erve Beck (2B), Bill Hallman (SS), Bob Wood (C), and Bill Hoffer (P).
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Hoffer allowed seven runs in the first two innings and the Blues failed to recover, as they lost the game 8–2, earning the first loss in American League history.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] In the second game of the season, Beck hit the first home run in American League history off pitcher John Skopec, but the Blues lost again, 7–3.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 9, 1901, Earl Moore threw the first no-hitter in the history of the franchise and the American League.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Blues lost to Chicago by a score of 4–2 despite allowing no hits.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 23, Cleveland scored nine runs with the bases empty and two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning to beat Washington 14–13.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The **1902 Cleveland Bronchos season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The team, known during this season as the "Bronchos" (or "Broncos"), finished in fifth place in the American League with a record of 69–67, 14 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] In 1902, the National League's Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Indians, then known unofficially as the Bronchos and subsequently renamed the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The **1903 Cleveland Naps season** was the third Major League Baseball season for the Cleveland American League team.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] After two seasons as the Bluebirds or Blues and also being called the Bronchos (or Broncos) in 1902, beginning with the 1903 season, the team was called the Naps in honor of star second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished third in the league with a record of 77–63, 15 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] The **1920 Cleveland Indians season** was the 20th season in franchise history.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] The Indians won the American League pennant and proceeded to win their first World Series title in the history of the franchise.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] Pitchers Jim Bagby, Stan Coveleski and Ray Caldwell combined to win 75 games.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] Despite the team's success, the season was perhaps more indelibly marked by the death of starting shortstop Ray Chapman, who died after being hit by a pitch on August 16.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] During the season, Jim Bagby became the last pitcher to win 30 games in one season for the Indians in the 20th century.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] On August 17, shortstop Ray Chapman died after being hit by a pitch in a game against the Yankees, becoming the second of only two Major League Baseball players to have died as a result of an injury received in a game (the first was Mike "Doc" Powers in 1909).
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] Note: Guy Morton was team leader in saves with 3.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] On October 10, 1920, which was the fifth game of the World Series, Bill Wambsganss of the Indians executed an unassisted triple play.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] He caught a line drive, touched second base, and tagged the runner coming from first base.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] On the same day, Elmer Smith hit the first grand slam in World Series history.
[src:1920-cleveland-indians-season/1920-cleveland-indians-season] During that same game, Indians pitcher Jim Bagby became the first pitcher to hit a home run in World Series history.
